   (Message) The failure is caused by `string.format()` treating an escaped
   percent sequence (`"%%"`) as if it were a real conversion that requires an
   argument.
   
   For the failing input:
   
   ```berry
   assert(s.format("%%") == "%")
   ```
   
   the call reaches `str_format()` in `src/be_strlib.c`.
   
   Program state at the failure:
   
   ```c
   static int str_format(bvm *vm)
   {
       int top = be_top(vm);              // top == 1
       if (top > 0 && be_isstring(vm, 1)) {
           int index = 2;                 // first value argument would be #2
           const char *format = be_tostring(vm, 1); // format == "%%"
           ...
   ```
   
   Only one Berry argument was passed: the format string itself. Therefore:
   
   ```c
   top == 1
   index == 2
   ```
   
   The loop finds the first `%` in `"%%"`:
   
   ```c
   const char *p = strchr(format, '%');
   ```
   
   Then it parses the format mode:
   
   ```c
   p = get_mode(p + 1, mode);
   ```
   
   For `"%%"`, `p + 1` points at the second `%`. `get_mode()` returns that
   second `%`, and `mode` becomes `"%%"`.
   
   At this point, `*p == '%'`, which should mean “emit a literal `%` and consume
   no argument.”
   
   But the current code checks for a missing argument before checking the
   conversion type:
   
   ```c
   if (index > top) {
       be_raise(vm, "runtime_error", be_pushfstring(vm,
           "bad argument #%d to 'format': no value", index));
   }
   switch (*p) {
       ...
   ```
   
   Since `index == 2` and `top == 1`, this raises:
   
   ```text
   runtime_error: bad argument #2 to 'format': no value
   ```
   
   That is wrong because `"%%"` is not supposed to consume argument #2 at all.
   
   The same bug would also break later tests such as:
   
   ```berry
   s.format("%i%%", 12)
   s.format("%i%%%i", 12, 13)
   s.format("%s%%", "foo")
   s.format("%.1f%%", 3.5)
   ```
   
   After formatting the real value, the trailing `"%%"` would again be treated
   as requiring another value.
   
   I verified the local fix by patching `src/be_strlib.c`, rebuilding, and
   running:
   
   ```sh
   ./berry tests/string.be
   ```
   
   After the fix, the test exits successfully.
   
   ##### Recommendation
   
   Minimal local fix: handle `%%` before the missing-argument check, and do not
   increment `index` for it.
   
   In `src/be_strlib.c`, in `str_format()`, immediately after:
   
   ```c
   p = get_mode(p + 1, mode);
   buf[0] = '\0';
   ```
   
   add handling for literal percent:
   
   ```c
   if (*p == '%') {
       pushstr(vm, "%", 1);
       concat2(vm);
       format = p + 1;
       continue;
   }
   ```
   
   So the relevant block becomes:
   
   ```c
   p = get_mode(p + 1, mode);
   buf[0] = '\0';
   
   if (*p == '%') {
       pushstr(vm, "%", 1);
       concat2(vm);
       format = p + 1;
       continue;
   }
   
   if (index > top) {
       be_raise(vm, "runtime_error", be_pushfstring(vm,
           "bad argument #%d to 'format': no value", index));
   }
   ```
   
   A more thorough root-cause fix would be to restructure `str_format()` so that
   argument validation happens inside only the conversion cases that actually
   consume an argument, and to add an explicit `case '%'` to the format
   dispatcher. That avoids this class of bug entirely:
   
   ```c
   switch (*p) {
   case '%':
       pushstr(vm, "%", 1);
       concat2(vm);
       format = p + 1;
       continue;
   
   case 'd': case 'i': case 'o':
   case 'u': case 'x': case 'X':
       if (index > top) {
           be_raise(vm, "runtime_error", be_pushfstring(vm,
               "bad argument #%d to 'format': no value", index));
       }
       ...
       ++index;
       break;
   
   ...
   }
   ```
   
   The key requirements are:
   
   1. `%` as a conversion specifier must emit a literal percent.
   2. It must not require an argument.
   3. It must not increment `index`.
